[[File:His Majesty's Theatre, Montreal.jpeg|thumb|His Majesty's Theatre, circa 1910.]] '''Her Majesty's Theatre''' (also known as '''His Majesty's Theatre''') was a theatre located on [[Guy Street]] in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada. For nearly 65 years it was one of the most important venues for [[orchestra]]l [[concert]]s, [[recital]]s, [[play (theatre)|plays]], [[opera]]s, and [[ballet]]s in that city.
[[File:Social. At His Majesty's Theatre BAnQ P48S1P05923.jpg|thumb|left|Spectators at a [[premiere]], His Majesty's Theatre, 1940.]]
Built in 1897-1898 during the reign of [[Queen Victoria]], the theatre was in continual operation until it was demolished in 1963. As the name of the theatre changed with the sex of the [[Monarchy of Canada|monarch of Canada]], the theatre was known as His Majesty's Theatre from 1901 to 1952, and then reverted to the title of Her Majesty's Theatre upon the accession of [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Elizabeth II]] in 1952.
It was the home of the [[Montreal Opera Company]] (1910-1913), the [[National Opera Company of Canada]] (1914), the [[Montreal Orchestra]] (1930-1941), and the [[Opera Guild of Montreal]] (1942-1963). The theatre was the main venue for the [[Montreal Festivals]] from 1940-1946.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0001602 |title=Her Majesty's Theatre |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608234759/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0001602 |archivedate=2011-06-08 |df= }}</ref>
