[[File:Alta Museum - panoramio (9).jpg|right|thumb|300px|World Heritage Rock Art Centre - Alta Museum]] [[File:1992.08.08 Helleristninger i Alta II.jpg|right|thumb|300 px|Rock carving at the Alta Museum site]]
The '''World Heritage Rock Art Centre - Alta Museum''' (''Verdensarvsenter for bergkunst – Alta Museum'') is located at [[Alta, Norway|Alta]] in [[Finnmark]], Norway. [[Norway]].<ref>[http://www.norgesverdensarv.no/the-rock-art-of-alta.134751.en.html ''The Rock Art of Alta'' (Norges Verdensarv)]</ref>
World Heritage Rock Art - Alta Museum is situated in [[Jiepmaluokta| Hjemmeluft]], a small bay on [[Altafjord]] near the [[Arctic Circle]].<ref>[http://www.alta.museum.no/sider/tekst.asp?side=76 ''Hjemmeluft'' (Alta Museum ligger i Alta kommune i Finnmark)]</ref> Alta Museum is northern Norway's most-visited summer museum, with more than 1,000 visitors each day.<ref name="tone">{{Cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3760/is_200307/ai_n9277073|title=Carved in Tone|accessdate=2008-03-22|year=2003|author=Mark Littlefield|work=Scandinavian Review}}</ref> It presents exhibitions on local culture and historic industries including the nearby prehistoric [[Rock carvings at Alta|rock carvings]] that form a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]. <ref>{{cite web|url= http://whc.unesco.org/en/documents/101445|title= Map - Hjemmeluft |publisher= UNESCO World Heritage Centre |accessdate= December 1, 2017}}</ref>
Alta Museum is situated at the site of early settlement of [[Finnmark]] dating from around 11,000 years ago.<ref name="recroc">{{Cite web|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-9171279_ITM|title=Records in the Rock|accessdate=2008-03-22|date=2001-01-01|work=International Wildlife}}</ref><ref name="pollu">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/904501.stm|title=Pollution Threatens Prehistoric Carvings|accessdate=2008-03-22|publisher=BBC News|date=2000-09-01 }}</ref> In 1973, the first rock carvings in Hjemmeluft were found. To date over 3,000 figures have been registered here. The museum opened in June 1991 and won the [[European Museum of the Year Award]] in 1993.<ref name="tone"/>
